---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import ReadinessCard from '../components/ReadinessCard.astro';

const email = 'stephaniemariepage@gmail.com';
const linkedin = 'https://linkedin.com/in/stephaniepagefrignoca';

const dimensions = [
  { name: 'Completeness', note: 'Is the field populated.' },
  { name: 'Standardization', note: 'Is the value in a consistent, usable format.' },
  { name: 'Accuracy', note: 'Is the value actually correct.' },
];

const tiers = [
  { name: 'Core', note: 'highest weight' },
  { name: 'Supporting', note: 'moderate weight' },
  { name: 'Supplemental', note: 'lowest weight' },
];

const classes = [
  { name: 'Ready', band: '90 to 100', dot: 'bg-ok' },
  { name: 'Near Ready', band: '70 to 89', dot: 'bg-ok' },
  { name: 'Partially Ready', band: '50 to 69', dot: 'bg-warn' },
  { name: 'Low Readiness', band: '30 to 49', dot: 'bg-bad' },
  { name: 'Not Ready', band: '0 to 29', dot: 'bg-bad' },
];

const proofPoints = [
  '~99K records scored',
  'Vendor report card',
  'Parent-account automation',
  'Live monitoring',
];
---

<Base title="Stephanie Frignoca | CRM data quality, measured honestly">
  <!-- Section 1 — Hero -->
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden">
    <div
      class="pointer-events-none absolute inset-x-0 top-0 h-[620px]"
      style="background: radial-gradient(52% 56% at 50% -6%, rgba(79,209,165,0.13), transparent 72%)"
    >
    </div>
    <div class="container-x relative grid gap-12 py-20 lg:grid-cols-[1.05fr_0.95fr] lg:items-center lg:gap-16 lg:py-28">
      <div class="animate-rise">
        <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-accent">
          CRM data quality, measured honestly
        </p>
        <h1 class="mt-5 text-4xl font-bold leading-[1.08] tracking-tight sm:text-5xl lg:text-6xl">
          Stop grading your CRM data <span class="text-accent">on a curve.</span>
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-6 max-w-xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-muted">
          A strong average hides the records that are quietly broken. Your routing,
          scoring, reporting, and AI workflows act on those records one at a time,
          not on the curve.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
          <a
            href="/scorecard"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-lg bg-accent px-5 py-3 text-sm font-semibold text-[#06231b] transition hover:brightness-110"
          >
            Run the Scorecard
          </a>
          <a
            href="/work"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-lg border border-line px-5 py-3 text-sm font-semibold text-fg transition hover:border-accent hover:text-accent"
          >
            Read the case study
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="animate-rise" style="animation-delay:0.12s">
        <ReadinessCard />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 2 — Averages lie -->
  <section class="border-t border-line/60">
    <div class="container-x py-20 lg:py-24">
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">
          A 95%-complete record can still be unusable.
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-muted">
          A composite data quality score rolls three different questions into one
          number: is the field filled in, is the value formatted consistently, is the
          value actually correct. One strong answer carries two weak ones, and the
          record reads as healthy when it is not.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-relaxed text-muted">
          Take a record that is 95% complete, perfectly standardized, and 20% accurate.
          A composite score calls it Near Ready. In reality, one in five of its
          values is wrong, and every workflow downstream is making decisions on those
          wrong values.
        </p>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-10 border-l-2 border-accent pl-5 text-xl font-semibold leading-snug sm:text-2xl">
        If teams have to verify it somewhere else, it is not the system of record.
        No curve rounds that up.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 3 — AI inherits your worst dimension -->
  <section class="border-t border-line/60">
    <div class="container-x py-20 lg:py-24">
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">
          AI workflows don't average your data. They act on it.
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-muted">
          Routing, scoring, segmentation, reporting, and AI agents consume your records
          one at a time. Each one inherits the worst dimension of the record in front
          of it, not the dataset average. A data foundation that looks fine in a
          quarterly dashboard can still feed wrong inputs into every automated decision
          you have.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg font-medium leading-relaxed">
          Robots can handle BAU once the data underneath them is trustworthy. They
          cannot fix a foundation that was never operationally defined as ready.
        </p>
        <a
          href={linkedin}
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          class="mt-6 inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 text-sm font-medium text-accent transition hover:brightness-110"
        >
          Discuss this on LinkedIn
          <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 4 — The framework: gated readiness -->
  <section class="border-t border-line/60">
    <div class="container-x py-20 lg:py-24">
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-accent">The framework</p>
        <h2 class="mt-4 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">
          Gated readiness: every dimension clears a floor, or the record is not ready.
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-muted">
          The honest alternative to a blended score is to measure each dimension on its
          own and refuse to average them away.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Three dimensions -->
      <div class="mt-10 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
        {dimensions.map((d) => (
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-line bg-surface p-5">
            <div class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-accent">{d.name}</div>
            <p class="mt-2 text-muted">{d.note}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <p class="mt-6 max-w-3xl text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted">
        Data quality has a standard vocabulary: completeness, validity, consistency,
        timeliness, uniqueness, accuracy. This framework consolidates it into the
        three dimensions that decide whether a record can be trusted for GTM, and
        scores each one on its own.
      </p>

      <!-- Field tiers -->
      <div class="mt-10">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-muted">Field tiers</h3>
        <p class="mt-3 max-w-3xl text-muted">
          Not every field carries equal weight. Fields are tiered into Core, Supporting,
          and Supplemental, and the scoring reflects what actually matters for a record
          you can use.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
          {tiers.map((t) => (
            <div class="rounded-lg border border-line bg-surface px-4 py-2 text-sm">
              <span class="font-semibold">{t.name}</span>
              <span class="text-muted"> &middot; {t.note}</span>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Five readiness classes -->
      <div class="mt-10">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-muted">
          Five readiness classes
        </h3>
        <div class="mt-4 grid grid-cols-2 gap-3 sm:grid-cols-5">
          {classes.map((c) => (
            <div class="rounded-lg border border-line bg-surface p-4">
              <div class={`h-1.5 w-8 rounded-full ${c.dot}`}></div>
              <div class="mt-3 text-sm font-semibold">{c.name}</div>
              <div class="mt-0.5 text-xs text-muted">{c.band}</div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- The gate -->
      <div class="mt-10 rounded-xl border border-accent/30 bg-accent/[0.05] p-6 sm:p-7">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-accent">
          <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
            <rect x="2.5" y="8" width="15" height="9.5" rx="1.5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6"/>
            <path d="M6 8V5.5a4 4 0 0 1 8 0V8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6"/>
          </svg>
          The gate
        </div>
        <p class="mt-3 text-lg leading-relaxed">
          If any critical dimension falls below its floor, the record drops to a failing
          class, no matter how strong the composite looks. A great average cannot buy
          back a fatal weakness.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3 text-muted">
          That single rule is the difference between a score that flatters you and a
          score you can run a GTM motion on.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 5 — The Scorecard -->
  <section class="border-t border-line/60">
    <div class="container-x py-20 lg:py-24">
      <div class="relative overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-line bg-surface p-8 sm:p-12">
        <div
          class="pointer-events-none absolute -right-24 -top-24 h-72 w-72 rounded-full"
          style="background: radial-gradient(closest-side, rgba(79,209,165,0.16), transparent)"
        >
        </div>
        <div class="relative max-w-2xl">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">
            See the framework run on a synthetic CRM, right in your browser.
          </h2>
          <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-muted">
            A live demo of the gated readiness model applied to a generated 60-record
            dataset. The scoring engine, the field tiers, the gate, and the five
            readiness classes all run client-side. Hit Refresh to draw a fresh sample.
            The rollup shows how many records the gate caught that a composite score
            would have waved through.
          </p>
          <div class="mt-5 inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-full border border-line bg-bg px-3 py-1 text-xs text-muted">
            <svg width="13" height="13" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <rect x="4" y="9" width="12" height="8" rx="1.5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6"/>
              <path d="M7 9V6.5a3 3 0 0 1 6 0V9" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6"/>
            </svg>
            100% client-side &middot; no upload &middot; no sign-in
          </div>
          <div class="mt-7">
            <a
              href="/scorecard"
              class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-lg bg-accent px-5 py-3 text-sm font-semibold text-[#06231b] transition hover:brightness-110"
            >
              Open the Scorecard
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 6 — Proof: the case study -->
  <section class="border-t border-line/60">
    <div class="container-x py-20 lg:py-24">
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-accent">Case study</p>
        <h2 class="mt-4 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">
          I built this for a Salesforce org with roughly 99,000 account records.
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-muted">
          At Cockroach Labs, the Core Account Profile program defined what a ready
          account record looks like and built the measurement around it. It scored the
          full account base, benchmarked enrichment vendors into a graded source
          hierarchy, automated parent-account hierarchy population, and stood up live
          monitoring across Salesforce and Snowflake.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-2.5">
        {proofPoints.map((p) => (
          <span class="rounded-lg border border-line bg-surface px-3 py-1.5 text-sm text-muted">
            {p}
          </span>
        ))}
      </div>
      <div class="mt-8">
        <a
          href="/work"
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-lg border border-line px-5 py-3 text-sm font-semibold text-fg transition hover:border-accent hover:text-accent"
        >
          Read the case study
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 7 — About teaser -->
  <section class="border-t border-line/60">
    <div class="container-x py-20 lg:py-24">
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-accent">About</p>
        <p class="mt-5 text-xl leading-relaxed sm:text-2xl">
          I am Stephanie Frignoca, a GTM data quality and CRM systems strategist. I turn
          messy GTM data into trusted, AI-ready revenue infrastructure: the frameworks,
          scoring models, and governance systems underneath segmentation, routing, and
          AI workflows. Salesforce Certified Administrator, with a BFA in design, which
          is why this site reads like a product and not a template.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-7">
          <a
            href="/about"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-lg border border-line px-5 py-3 text-sm font-semibold text-fg transition hover:border-accent hover:text-accent"
          >
            More about Stephanie
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 8 — Contact / closing CTA -->
  <section class="border-t border-line/60">
    <div class="container-x py-20 lg:py-28">
      <div
        class="rounded-2xl border border-line p-8 text-center sm:p-14"
        style="background: linear-gradient(180deg, #0f1214 0%, #08090b 100%)"
      >
        <h2 class="mx-auto max-w-2xl text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">
          Open to the right full-time role, and to consulting through Page Frignoca LLC.
        </h2>
        <p class="mx-auto mt-5 max-w-xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-muted">
          If your CRM data is not ready for the AI workflows you are about to point at
          it, that is the work I do. Let's talk.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-3">
          <a
            href={`mailto:${email}`}
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-lg bg-accent px-5 py-3 text-sm font-semibold text-[#06231b] transition hover:brightness-110"
          >
            Email Stephanie
          </a>
          <a
            href={linkedin}
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-lg border border-line px-5 py-3 text-sm font-semibold text-fg transition hover:border-accent hover:text-accent"
          >
            Connect on LinkedIn
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
